DIV1.HEAD: THE COUNTRY-JOURNAL Extraordinary.
DIV1.P: 'TIS evident, that many Designs, which might have been highly beneficial to the Publick, have miscarried, only by wanting a regular Scheme of Execution; to guard against which, I have taken some Precautions, and such as, 'tis hoped, may render my Appearances of universal Influ∣ence and Advantage; but that the Expecta∣tions of Friends may keep Pace with my un∣wearied Endeavours in their Service, I look upon myself under a Necessity of dedica∣ting the extraordinary Labours of this Day, not so much to review what has been done, as to let them know what will be done.

THE Scene of Action, which for some Time has lain altogether without Doors, will now be partly within; where, if our Pro∣ceedings
are not properly countenanc'd, all past Attempts will prove insignificant, and in vain.
No Methods, therefore, shall be untry'd to procure the desired Success; nothing shall be omitted that Malice can invent; or Rage enforce.

MY dearest Friends, and Countrymen, I am going to open my self to you without Reserve: All Disguises and Fiction laid a∣side; and for once I'll treat you with Sin∣cerity and Truth; neither of which I could have any Assistance from, but upon this particular Occasion.

YOU cannot but know the GRAND AFFAIR resolv'd on by us, was, to attack the Government; and either to embarrass that, or push for a general Uneasiness; the Management of which was left to myself, Dean S —, a late SECRETARY, W — S— Esq and a few others: How we have alrea∣dy discharged the great Trust reposed in us, or are able to discharge it in Time to come, will best appear from the present Disco∣veries.

'TIS sufficiently known that the most pro∣bable Means have been us'd to execute the latter Part of our Commission; the for∣mer, is our proper Work in the approach∣ing Season: We have every Way, consistent with our own Safety, striven to asperse and blacken the M—y; we have not only had our weekly Hirelings to spread Scandal through the Kingdom, but have supported a more private Correspondence, and travelling
Emissaries, to confirm that Scandal; and to propagate false Reports and Stories con∣triv'd on Purpose to render those intrusted with the Administration obnoxious.

THESE have not been altogether with∣out Success; and in the North, we seem ful∣ly to have gain'd our Point: But that I may not rob him of the Honour to whom 'tis most justly due, I must acknowledge this is an Acquisition entirely owing to that disin∣terested Patriot and Statesman W— S— Esq his little invenom'd Libel did the Business, and spread Contagion as epidemical as the new Distemper among the Horses; which, tho' it has at present only infected the Beasts, may, if not timely prevented, be fatal to Men, and prove more universally destructive.

BEING indefatigable in the Service, he put that elaborate excellent Piece to Press at NEWCASTLE, and dispers'd it among all our Friends in that Part of Eng∣land; so that now there is not a Malecontent, or Jacobite of US in the Nation, but is fully convinc'd that the present M — y are E∣nemies to their King and Country; that they are not fit to be continued in the chief Direction; that they have been lavish of the publick Money; and acted inconsistent with the Trust repos'd in them, and betray'd their Country, by voting their present Ma∣jesties a larger Revenue for supporting the Honour and Dignity of the Crown, and main∣taining their numerous and illustrious Fa∣mily, than was given to the late Queen,
who had no such Royal Family to maintain; and that this was such an EXORBITANT EX∣PENCE, as they are convinc'd, the Promoters of should never be forgiven.

BUT they are still better convinc'd than all this; and as firmly believe as we do ourselves, that Things will never go right, till we have the Management of them; till myself, and those under whose auspicious Influences Great Britain so eminently flourish'd, during the four last Years of Queen Anne, are plac'd at the Helm, and have again the Prime, the sole Direction.

THERE was a Time, indeed, these were a little wrong, and, out of a mistaken Notion of Good to their Country, made a few in∣effectual Offers to set aside the Hanover Succes∣sion; but they are now better informed; we have contracted the most sacred Friendship: Our Interests and Views are now the same, and what they chiefly propose by their pre∣sent Struggle to be again employ'd, is, to let their Countrymen see that they are the properest to be trusted with the Defence of those who they have formerly betray'd.

THO' these present Attainments may be thought considerable, yet they bear but small Proportion to those we promise our∣selves in the approaching S — n, which we don't doubt making remarkable, by a tho∣rough Change, and an entire Dismission of all those our Disappointments have made us Enemies to.

THEY may pretend to despise our At∣tacks as impotent, or as envious and un∣just; and defy the Utmost we dare attempt:
But we know our Strength too well to be thus baffled; 'tis our unalterable Resolu∣tion to pursue them to their Destruction, or in∣sult the P — e that protects them.

NOTHING shall satisfy us but to see them sacrificed to our personal Resentments, who were the long-try'd and faithful Servants of his late Majesty, and the first Glories of a Reign stain'd by a Disesteem of those, whose Intrepidity, Rosolution, and Loyalty so largely contributed to the preserving the Honour and Interest of the Illustrious House of Hanover in this Nation, even in the most dangerous Times, against the very Persons who are chief in the present Op∣position, and once bid fair to have dispos∣sess'd us of our Liberties, and depriv'd us of the present Royal Family, or oblig'd us to have redeem'd both with Blood.

SOME may be weak enough to think, that whatever Alterations may hereafter be made in the Administration, their Royal Master will always shew a just Value for those, who have so steadily adher'd to his own, and their Country's Interest; and that they'll meet with an Approbation due to their Fidelity and Abilities; that his Majesty will not act by them inconsistent with that high Veneration his Subjects have of his Majesty's Goodness and Wisdom; or contrary to what has ever been so distin∣guishingly the Peculiar of the august House of Hanover, no more to forget their Friends, than be afraid of their Enemies: They may go yet further, and imagine, that no Treat∣ment
will appear that may discourage, in any future Times of Difficulty or Danger, the honest, the loyal Attempts of Friends to the Protestant Interest and Succession.
BUT we are prepar'd for the worst that can happen, and not to be discouraged if Things should take such an unhappy Turn.

WE despise every Fence, and don't doubt letting it be seen, that the most sacred Barrier is to be forc'd: 'Tis not the Royal Favour, or untainted Loyalty; 'tis not an unexceptionable Conduct, or the universal Affection of the People for them; 'tis not the great Happiness they have been to these Kingdoms, and to Europe, or the greater Good they are capable of; 'tis not their be∣ing valuable publick Blessings; born to serve and save their Country, shall secure them from our unappeasable Rage; and prevent our saying the vilest Things of them, or doing the basest by them.

HOW far we have behaved agreeable to so laudable a Resolution hitherto, let the World determine; if we have been defective, we are resolv'd to make amends, by most strictly adhering to it in our future Proceedings: There is nothing so criminal in the worst of Characters, but we have apply'd to those in Power, because they are in Power; and en∣deavour'd, if possible, to stab them thus in the dark, who we are unable more publickly to destroy.

WE are but an inconsiderable Faction, 'tis true; but we can easily be come a mischie∣vous one: We have popular Methods enough
in our Power to make us, at least, be thought numerous, and appear formidable; and we could not answer it to our King, not to make use of them: We are capable of Assassination; and in P — 's CAUSE, as 'tis call'd, the most cowardly Attacks are justifiable; the more base, the more proper.

DEPEND upon us then, my Friends, in the approaching critical Juncture, for all that Men exasperated by the most aggravating Disappointments dare do: The COUNTRY JOURNAL shall continue to incense the Po∣pulace, and behave to the Government with unprecedented Indecencies and Insolence: It shall treat the M— y as publick Plunde∣rers, as the Invaders of our Rights and Pri∣vileges, Enemies to Liberty, and our E∣stablishment in Church and State; who have supported themselves by Rapine and Oppression, and grown rich by the Desola∣tion and Spoils of their native Country: It shall represent them as most treacherous and perfidious, more base and black than even B — l— ke.

WHILE the Attack is thus furiously car∣rying on without Doors, with equal Justice, and we hope Success, it shall be supported from within; myself, and good Ally WILL S— will bellow EXORBITANT EX∣PENCES, BRIBERY, and CORRUPTION, the bottomless Gulph, SECRET SERVICES, the NATIONAL DEBT, Hidden Truths, and Concealed Iniquities, and rage, and foam, rather than be despised and disregarded, as we have been; we will be Heard, or the
Peace of the — shall be daily broke, and the Dispatch of publick Business interrupted.

WE have already by us some excellent S—s, and other, Performances suited to several subsequent Occasions; being now determined what to speak, and what to print, then; the former is proper to WILL S — and myself; the latter is for a Season, committed chiefly to the conduc∣cting of that finish'd Statesman, HARRY GAMBOL, and Orthodox Prelate, Dean POLLY∣GLOT; and from the exemplary Piety of the one, and most consummate Skill in Politicks of the other; and from the strong Affection of both to our happy Constitution, what is there great and good which might conduce to the Advancement of Religion, or Welfare of the State, that may not be expected?

THUS accomplish'd, resolv'd and prepar'd, we set out the proper Agents of such valua∣ble, such honest Undertakings; Underta∣kings worthy ourselves, and which we alone are equal to: Revenge and personal Pique as∣sist us.

WE don't pretend to charge any because they are guilty; that would be doing Violence to our establish'd Characters; no, we charge them because they are in the M— y, and we are not; this has been the only Reason of our past Conduct, and stands sufficient to justify the worst we can offer at; we have loaded them with a Multitude of Crimes, and shall still be adding to the Number we don't pretend to prove one Crime, o
make good the least Mismanagement against them: It may in Time abundantly an∣swer our Purpose, to impose upon the People.

BUT if in so material a Point our for∣mer ill Success should attend us, we have still a reserved Game to Play: 'Tis but carrying our Enmity something higher, to make ourselves most considerable: We have already reviv'd the dying Hopes of Faction, and the Jacobites, who were universally dejected, and had given up their Cause for lost, have thrown away their Despon∣dency, and rais'd great Expectations from us; there is no Disaffection in the Nation but what we have occasion'd; and 'tis in our Power to carry it to any Degree we please: His Majesty has not an Enemy, but what is a Friend to us.

THUS knowing our Strength, and regard∣less of the Event, we are firmly resolv'd to push our Resentments to the utmost, and either become superior to those we have sworn Enmity to, or risque a Distress and general Confusion; and, as it has been the only Rule of our past Conduct, so it may as certainly be expected to be, that every Proceeding of the present Government, whether abroad or at home, shall be cen∣sured and revil'd, because such is a Proceed∣ing of the present Government.

AFTER this, let them talk of defying us if they please, insist upon their Inno∣cence, and challenge us to prove so much as one Particular, in which they have be∣tray'd their Trust, acted unbecoming
the high Stations they are in, or incon∣sistent with the Honour of their King, and the real Interest of their Country: Our Busi∣ness is only to assert, not to venture up∣on the Proof; and if we can but gain Belief, 'tis all we are at present sollicitous about.

WE smile at People's saying, That to be influenced by such an exasperated malevo∣lent Party, would argue the utmost Weak∣ness in a C—t; 'twould be the greatest Tes∣timony of Irresolution; and that they may thank God, Great Britain's Monarch is too good, too wise, too steady, to regard what is only the Effect of a private Quarrel, and personal Ani∣mosity, and is look'd upon as such by all Men of Sense in the Nation.

THUS you see what you are to depend upon from us, and what we depend upon for ourselves; our Expectations are large, and not to be lessen'd; Success will crown all: Nor is it any Damp to our Hopes, to be told, that there are none of us equal to that Administration we would push into, but are such as already are contemn'd or ab∣horr'd; not a Man, but their Country has just Cause to dread their being again employ'd, as Persons no wise Government would ven∣ture to trust; SUCH, as no Prince would rely on, that has any Regard for his own Ho∣nour, or a just Concern for the Welfare of his People.

CLOSER.SIGNED: I am, Messieurs, Most devotedly Your Servant, CALEB D'ANVERS.
